  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a lived reality for many students and professionals, especially those from underrepresented groups. Having grown up in a small town near Philadelphia, I remember the quiet anxiety that came with being the only person in my class who wasn't sure if they belonged in science. My parents, both educated but not in STEM fields, often said, 'Just do your best,' but that didn't always ease the weight of others' expectations. As a creative thinker, I've always felt that stereotypes can be a kind of invisible barrier, a shadow that makes people question their own abilities before they even start. In my retirement, I've spent time reflecting on how these biases affect young minds. For instance, when I watch documentaries about science education, I see how a single comment from a teacher can shift a student's confidence. The key isn't to fix the problem but to create spaces where everyone feels safe to explore without fear. We should address stereotype threat by integrating inclusive storytelling into STEM curricula—showing diverse scientists who've overcome similar doubts. It's not about changing the system overnight but nurturing a culture where curiosity is celebrated, not criticized. In my community, I've seen how board games and cinema can spark interest in science, so why not use those same tools to build confidence? Ultimately, addressing stereotype threat means recognizing that every child has the potential to contribute to STEM, and we must do everything in our power to make that potential visible.",
